LÂM CHẤN KHẢI is an Intern Network/System Administrator, currently pursuing a Bachelor's in Computer Network with a 3.3 GPA and intermediate English proficiency. With no commercial experience, their core expertise is rooted in academic projects and foundational knowledge of network architecture and system administration. This includes deep understanding of the OSI model, TCP/IP model, and Hybrid Window Server environments. Key areas of focus encompass Networking, Redundancy, Security, VLAN, OSPF, RIP, TRUNKING, ACI, NAT, DNS, DHCP, VPN, RADIUS, NAP, ADDS, CA, Group Policy, GPO management, Folder Redirection, Auditing, Disaster Recovery, Load balancing (NLB), Backup strategies, System restore procedures, and Troubleshooting. Their academic portfolio includes designing and configuring a bank network simulation emphasizing redundancy, load balancing, and security using HSRP, NAT, ACL, SVI, and Packet Tracer. They also successfully deployed and configured a corporate wireless network utilizing AP and WLC via Packet Tracer, and constructed basic network topologies with GNS3. This strong theoretical and practical foundation is further solidified by completing a Cisco Certified Network Associate (CCNA) course and holding JNCIA-Junos certification.
Technically, LÂM CHẤN KHẢI is proficient with network analysis and simulation tools such as Wireshark, TCP dump, Packet Tracer, and GNS3. They possess foundational knowledge in cloud security monitoring platforms including Azure Sentinel and Azure Security Center. Their hands-on experience extends to configuring and managing Windows Server and Linux environments, implementing advanced networking concepts like HSRP, ACL, SVI, AP, WLC, and performing critical system administration tasks such as DNS, DHCP, VPN, RADIUS, NAP, ADDS, CA, GPO management, Folder Redirection, Auditing, Disaster Recovery, Load balancing (NLB), Backup strategies, and System restore procedures. This profile highlights a dedicated individual with a robust academic background and practical project experience in network design, security, and system administration.